For a permutation p1, p2, …, pN of length N, a contiguous subsegment pl, pl+1, …, pr is called an “interval”

if, when sorted, it forms a sequence of consecutive integers.

For example, [7, 8, 9], [3, 1, 5, 4, 2], [4, 3], and [2] are intervals, whereas [3, 5] and [5, 3] are not.



Given two permutations P and Q, we define them as framed interval isomorphic if for any 1<=i<=j<=N,

the subsegment [i,j] is an interval in P if and only if it is an interval in Q (i.e., the conditions are either both true or both false).

The framed interval isomorphism relation is an equivalence relation, thus allowing us to define equivalence classes.



